{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G4 child-consistency audit — parent 72d5 (Migrate the LLM gates onto the workflow engine) × child 0408 (Complete the workflow plan-review verify/coach LIVE plumbing + re-default gate_engine to workflow)]\n\nChecked all 7 cross-child interaction modes against the WHOLE sibling roster (B1 723c, B2 6b06, B3 dc58, B4 101a, B5 f12d, B6 7e48, B-RETIRE 961b, B-DM 5506, B-UX 92fa). One high-confidence finding (conflicting-assumptions / scope-overlap with B5 f12d). The other six modes read benign — see footnotes.\n\n═══════════════════════════════════════\nFINDING 1 — Conflicting assumptions + scope overlap: B5 (f12d) is CLOSED + SIGNED asserting `gate_engine` already defaults to \"workflow\" with a live-correct plan-review path, while 0408 (and the live tree) establish that this is FALSE — the same end-state is claimed done by one sibling and not-yet-done by another.\n─────────────────────────────────────\n- criteria:\n  • parent AC4 (\"the bespoke orchestrator path is cut over to the workflow path … DEFAULTING to the workflow path; close/claim gates keep working\")\n  • parent Success Criterion (\"plan-review … runs on the ONE workflow-engine substrate, validated by offline planned-trace parity\")\n  • 0408 AC2/AC4 (live review-plan returns real PASS/BLOCK; re-flip default to workflow)\n  • B5 (f12d) AC1 (\"…defaulting to the workflow path\") + its signed completion-verification PASS\n\n- location: gates `verify.gate_engine` default (src/rebar/config.py:276–283); the workflow plan-review verify/coach prompt steps (src/rebar/llm/workflow/runs.py RunnerAgentStep, gates/plan-review.yaml); bespoke listing builders in src/rebar/llm/plan_review/passes.py (pass2_verify/pass4_coach).\n\n- evidence:\n  • B5 (f12d) is CLOSED + SIGNED; its completion-verification PASS comment asserts: \"src/rebar/config.py:276: gate_engine: str = \\\"workflow\\\" is the default\" and AC1 \"defaulting to workflow … MET.\"\n  • The live tree contradicts that signed claim: config.py:283 reads `gate_engine: str = \"bespoke\"`, with the docstring (config.py:276–282) stating the workflow plan-review verify \"degrades to INDETERMINATE live — a B2 offline blind spot the B5 cutover surfaced.\"\n  • RunnerAgentStep.run (runs.py:131–137) supplies ONLY {ticket_id, ticket_context, repo_path} into resolve_prompt — confirming the plan-review verifier/coach prompts' required `{{plan}}` (and findings/surviving listing) are NOT provided on the live path, exactly as 0408's Why states.\n  • PR #42 flipped the default back to bespoke as a hotfix (0408 Why; B-RETIRE comment 1782505678304851001).\n  • B5's own verifier hedged the gap: \"No full end-to-end live signing test over the workflow path exists\" — the offline/structural verification that signed B5 could not see the live blind spot.\n\n- scenarios:\n  1. A reviewer reconciling the roster sees B5 SIGNED-complete for \"default = workflow / live gate cut over,\" yet 0408 (open) says that exact deliverable is broken and must be re-done — two siblings own the same config-default end-state with contradictory completion status.\n  2. If B5 is trusted as signed-done and 0408 is deprioritized/dropped, the epic ships with `gate_engine=bespoke` permanently — i.e. plan-review NEVER actually runs on the workflow substrate live, silently defeating the parent's central Success Criterion despite a green/signed sibling.\n  3. B-RETIRE (961b) is gated on 0408 (its own comment), but B5's signed evidence would suggest the workflow path is already the proven sole-capable gate — a reader could mistakenly let B-RETIRE proceed off B5's stale signature, removing the only working (bespoke) plan-review gate.\n\n- impact: The sibling set is internally inconsistent on a load-bearing claim: B5's signed AC1/end-state (\"workflow is the working default\") is not true in the tree, and 0408 silently re-owns the same deliverable without B5 being corrected/reopened. The epic's primary Success Criterion (plan-review running live on the one workflow substrate) hinges entirely on 0408 landing, yet a signed sibling already attests it as done. This is a real ordering/overlap artifact, not a duplication of independent work: B5 over-scoped its signed verdict (it set default=workflow on an unsound live path, then PR #42 reverted it), and 0408 is the corrective.\n\n- checklist_item: \"Check the 7 cross-child modes … conflicting assumptions … scope overlap … each detected mode is a finding.\"\n\n- suggested_fix: Make the inconsistency explicit and acknowledged in the plan: (a) add an explicit dependency/cross-reference 0408 → f12d on the FACE of both tickets (0408 already carries a `discovered_from` f12d link — surface it as the rationale that B5's \"default=workflow\" claim is superseded), and annotate B5 (f12d) that its AC1 \"defaulting to workflow\" held only structurally/offline and was reverted by PR #42 pending 0408; (b) state in 0408 that it COMPLETES B5's AC1/AC2 on the live path (verify/coach `{{plan}}`+findings plumbing) rather than presenting as an independent task, so no reader treats B5's signature as proof the workflow gate is the working default; (c) ensure B-RETIRE (961b) — which already notes the 0408 gate — keys its precondition off 0408's completion, not B5's signed status, before deleting the bespoke path.\n\n═══════════════════════════════════════\nModes read benign (no finding):\n\n(1) Implicit shared state — 0408 mutates shared surfaces also touched by B2/B5: gates/plan-review.yaml, RunnerAgentStep (runs.py), the gate_engine default, and the passes.py listing builders. But 0408 explicitly EXTRACTS the bespoke builders into a shared helper \"no duplication\" and sequences itself after B5/PR #42; the sharing is acknowledged and ordered, not a hidden concurrent mutation. (The B5↔0408 contradiction on the gate_engine VALUE is captured in Finding 1.)\n\n(3) Dependency gap — 0408 depends on B5's cutover machinery + the bespoke passes.py builders. B-RETIRE (961b) explicitly KEEPS `passes` and gates its own bespoke-removal on 0408 (comment 1782505678304851001), so 0408's reused helper survives retirement. Properly ordered; no gap.\n\n(5) Ordering violation — 0408 is correctly last among live-path work (after B5 cutover, after B6's sample removal on the hotfix branch) and before B-RETIRE. Sequencing is consistent.\n\n(6) Consumer impact — flipping the default to workflow changes live claim-gate behaviour, but interface tests pin REBAR_VERIFY_GATE_ENGINE=bespoke (per B5's notes) to keep validating the fallback, and the new live smoke test is REBAR_MCP_ALLOW_LLM-gated. No unhandled consumer break.\n\n(7) Residual references — the shared listing helper 0408 extracts from passes.py is preserved by B-RETIRE's \"keep passes\" clause; no dangling reference to a removed bespoke symbol.\n\nANTI-FP note: The B5↔0408 conflict is reported as a single high-confidence finding because the live tree (config.py:283 = \"bespoke\"; runs.py only supplies 3 vars) OBJECTIVELY contradicts B5's signed assertion (config.py = \"workflow\", AC1 MET), and the two siblings own the same end-state with opposite completion status. The remaining modes are filtered out under the benign-reading rule."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782508099672096001,"uuid":"8fb4c7b3-f7e4-4441-9046-da1489ee06c8"}